SAT Scores in New York City

This notebook will take a look at SAT Scores from several high schools in New York City along with demographic, geogrphic and other information about the schools.

After reading in, preparing and combining multiple data sets about high schools folowing questions can be discussed:

  • What variables have the biggest influence (in terms of correlation) on the total SAT scores?
  • Are there significant differences between districts/boroughs?
  • Is demographic information important?
  • Can a ranking of the schools be explained by demographic or geographic information?
  • Are the SAT fair? Concerning the allegations about the SAT being unfair to certain racial groups or biased by gender?

NOTE

This analysis of SAT scores serves exclusively as a descriptive analysis. Everything that is computed with the data is used to gain some informative insights from and for the current data only. The analysis should not be used as a predictive. Conclusions about future data can only be carefully suggested.

The Data

The base of this little project will be a data set about SAT scores and a data set which contains information about each high school. Such as the school name, the address, ell-programs, school type and others. Both data sets can be downloaded from the web site: data.cityofnewyork.us.

Additional Data

To enhance the investigation on SAT scores supplementing data sets are taken into account. All the following data sets can also be downloaded from this web site: data.cityofnewyork.us.

  • Math Test Results; A data set about the New York State Mathematics Test for grades 3-8.
  • Class Size; This data set contains information about class sizes. The average class size for each school, each program type and grade was carried out into this data set.
  • AP Test Results; This data set contains the New York City school level College Board AP results for 2010.
  • Graduation Outcome; A data set about the cohorts of 2001 through 2006 (classes of 2005 through 2010). The cohort consists of all students who first entered 9th grade in a given school year (e.g., the cohort of 2006 entered 9th grade in the 2006-2007 school years). Graduates are defined as those students earning either a Local or Regents diploma.
  • Demographics; Annual school accounts of NYC public school student populations served by grade, special programs, ethnicity, gender and Title I funded programs.
  • School Survey; Survey results provide insight into a school’s learning environment and contribute a measure of diversification that goes beyond test scores on the Progress Report. Survey questions assess the community’s opinions on academic expectations, communication, engagement, and safety and respect. School leaders can use survey results to better understand their own school’s strengths and target areas for improvement.
  • School Attendance; DOE attendance and enrollment statistics broken down by school district

Read in and Prepare all the Data for Combination

Each school in New York City has a unique identification code called DBN, District Borough Number. So the data sets can be merged based on this DBN. First read in the data.

sat_results <- read.csv(file='~/education/SAT_Results.csv', header=TRUE)
ap_results <- read.csv(file='~/education/AP_Results.csv', header=TRUE, sep=",")
math_results <- read.csv(file='~/education/Math_Results.csv', header=TRUE)

demographics <- read.csv(file='~/education/demographics.csv', header=TRUE)
attendance <- read.csv(file='~/education/attendance.csv', header=TRUE)

hs_directory <- read.csv(file='~/education/hs_directory.csv', header=TRUE)
colnames(hs_directory)[1] <- "DBN"

Adding in the Surveys

The data set on student, parent, and teacher surveys about the quality of schools is also a potentially interesting data set to look at. The surveys include information about the perceived safety of each school, academic standards, and more.

First the data sets are read in and then combined to on single set called survey.

There are two school-level data files from the 2011 NYC School Survey available. School-level data is available in one file for all community schools (file name: survey.csv) and one file for all District 75 schools (file name: survey_75.csv). These files display one line of information for each school, by DBN, that includes the response rate for each school, the number of surveys submitted, the size of the eligible survey population at each school, question scores, the percentage of responses selected, and the count of responses selected.

Along with the data there can be a data dictionary file downloaded. Based on this file any extraneous columns can be removed.

survey_gened <- read.csv2(file='C:/Users/Anna Sofia/Documents/Portfolio/education/survey.csv', header=TRUE)
survey_75 <- read.csv2(file='C:/Users/Anna Sofia/Documents/Portfolio/education/survey_75.csv', header=TRUE)

survey_all <- merge(survey_gened, survey_75, by="dbn", all = TRUE)
colnames(survey_all)[1] <- "DBN"

survey <- subset(survey_all, select = c(DBN, rr_s.x, rr_t.x, rr_p.x, N_s.x, N_t.x, N_p.x, saf_p_11.x, com_p_11.x, eng_p_11.x, aca_p_11.x, saf_t_11.x, com_t_11.x, eng_t_11.x, aca_t_11.x, saf_s_11.x, com_s_11.x, eng_s_11.x, aca_s_11.x, saf_tot_11.x, com_tot_11.x, eng_tot_11.x, aca_tot_11.x)) #23

Computing new Variables

Rather than the individual SAT scores the total SAT score is interesting for this investigation. Unavailable scores are marked with an “s”. So converting the scores into integers has to happen after some data manipulation. First all unavailable values (“s”) are determined and marked as NA. Then the scores can be converted to integers. The same needs to be done for the ap_results data set.

For the question of possible differences between districts or borough, those variables are determined by reading the district and borough number out of the DBN.

# indicate missing values as NA
sat_results[sat_results$Num_of_SAT_Test_Takers == "s", "Num_of_SAT_Test_Takers"] <- NA
sat_results[sat_results$SAT_Critical_Reading_Avg_Score == "s", "SAT_Critical_Reading_Avg_Score"] <- NA
sat_results[sat_results$SAT_Math_Avg_Score == "s", "SAT_Math_Avg_Score"] <- NA
sat_results[sat_results$SAT_Writing_Avg_Score == "s", "SAT_Writing_Avg_Score"] <- NA

# now the values can be converted to numeric
sat_results <- within(sat_results, {
                      Num_of_SAT_Test_Takers <- as.numeric(as.character(Num_of_SAT_Test_Takers))
                      SAT_Critical_Reading_Avg_Score <- as.numeric(as.character(SAT_Critical_Reading_Avg_Score))
                      SAT_Math_Avg_Score <- as.numeric(as.character(SAT_Math_Avg_Score))
                      SAT_Writing_Avg_Score <- as.numeric(as.character(SAT_Writing_Avg_Score)) })

# compute the total SAT score
sat_results <- within(sat_results, 
                      SAT_Total_Score <- SAT_Critical_Reading_Avg_Score + SAT_Math_Avg_Score + SAT_Writing_Avg_Score)

# determine District and Borough out of the DBN
sat_results <- within(sat_results, {
  BOROUGH <- as.factor(substr(DBN, start = 3, stop = 3))
  DISTRICT <- as.factor(substr(DBN, start = 1, stop = 2))
})

Combining all the Data Sets

Now all data sets can be combined into one. Based on the DBN all data sets are joined.

merge_1 <- merge(math_results, survey, by="DBN")
merge_2 <- merge(merge_1, ap_results, by="DBN", all=TRUE)
merge_3 <- merge(merge_2, class_size_unique, by="DBN")
merge_4 <- merge(merge_3, demographics, by="DBN")
merge_5 <- merge(merge_4, graduation, by="DBN", all=TRUE)
merge_6 <- merge(merge_5, hs_directory, by="DBN")
sat_nyc <- merge(merge_6, sat_results, by="DBN", all=TRUE)

Missing SAT Scores

The main purpose of this notebook is to investigate SAT results, so it makes not much sense to include data without SAT results. Maybe for other questions, which are not regarding the SAT results on the first glance, other data without matching SAT scores is important. Here the analysis is emphasized on the SAT scores. So all schools without those are removed from the data set.

One could impute missing SAT scores with an average or something else, but replacing missing values with the mean of a column is statistical malpractice and not really necessary here, since there are only 56 missing values. So after removing the NA’s entirely there are still 421 observations from the before 477 left.

sat_na_omit <- na.omit(sat_results)
sat_nyc_na_omit <- merge(merge_6, sat_na_omit, by="DBN", all.y=TRUE)
nrow(sat_results)
## [1] 477
nrow(sat_na_omit)
## [1] 421

Now there is one single data set which contains SAT scores as well as all the additional information. For each school, each DBN, all values are carried out in one row in the data set.

The combined data set can now be investigated. Following questions are discussed: * What variables have the biggest inlfuence (in terms of correlation) on the total SAT scores? * Are there significant differences between districts/boroughs? * Are demographic information important? * Can a ranking of the schools be explained by demographic or geographic information? * Are the SAT fair? Concerning the allegations about the SAT being unfair to certain racial groups or gender biased?

Taking a look at the raw scores (the total SAT score) one can see that no school reached the maximal possible score of 2400. Most schools reach an average score between 1100 and 1250 points. 

summary(sat_nyc_na_omit$SAT_Total_Score)

Correlations

Let’s now take a closer look at the individual variables that might have a correlation with the SAT scores. First only numeric variables are taken into account, such as the percentage of ELL students at a school.

If a high schooler indicates that a language other than English is spoken in his/her home, the child is given the New York State Identification Test for English Language Learners (NYSITELL), which is designed to determine English language proficiency. Students who score below a State determined level on the assessment are identified as ELLs, and are therefore entitled to ELL programs and services.

Attending school while not speaking the teaching language proficiently is considered to be difficult, therefore a negative correlation between ell_percent and SAT scores is expected.

There are several points and insights that might need to be explored.

  • ell_percent correlate strongly negatively with SAT scores, as expected.
  • The same states for sped_percent, the percentage of students that are eligible for special-education services correlates strongly negatively with SAT scores.
  • The survey responses do not correlate highly with SAT scores, except the Student response rate and the Safety and Respects scores. It may be, however, interesting that most survey responses correlate positively with SAT scores, whereas the Teacher respond rate correlates negatively with SAT scores.
  • The percentage of males correlates negatively with SAT scores, whereas the percentage of females correlates positively with SAT scores.
  • It is surprising that total enrollment correlates rather positively with SAT scores, because one would think that smaller schools which could focus more on the student would have higher scores.
  • It is also surprising that the number of test takers correlates quite strongly with SAT scores.
  • There seems to be a strong racial inequality in SAT scores.
  • The number of AP Test Takers correlates highly positively with SAT scores.

On the other hand the correlation between SAT scores and the Safety and Respects scores might be explainable. If a school provides a safe and respectful learning environment, students might learn better. Especially if teachers feel safe and respected their patience and ability to teach individually might improve, which also reflect on their students.

  theme(legend.position="bottom")
## Warning: Removed 296 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

The quite highly positive correlation between the number of students which took an AP test and the SAT scores is worth being further investigated. When looking at the scatterplot above, one can actually see the positive correlation. However there seems to be a cluster in the right top area which may be a group of observations that are biased. All high schools which have a percentage of AP test takers higher than 30% are listed below. Those are all schools with an admission test so highly selective schools. It seems reasonable that especially those schools would have a high proportion of AP test takers. After removing those schools and computing the correlation again one can see that it has decreased. The correlation between AP test takers and SAT scores is less high. There seems to be now a little bit more variety.

Since several states use Advanced Placement data for accountability purposes and to rank high schools a critical analysis is more or less inevitable. An overview of studies gives this article here. The authors also ask if legal mandates and financial incentives for AP courses are good investments of resources. They also conducted as a whole that increasing AP participation does not increase the overall academic achievement or school quality at the group (e.g., high school, racial/ethnic group, and nation) level. This led one researcher to state, “Clearly, offering AP alone will not magically turn a failing school into a successful one.”

The greatest advantages of AP programs lie in the academic achievements for those students who actually took the test.

What can NOT be concluded

This analysis of SAT scores has shown some interesting insights which are worth to be further investigated. However, there are limits to it (like to any other data analysis). For example regarding gender and race percentages, the highly negative correlation between hispanic students and SAT scores does not mean, that hispanic students do worse than other students on the SAT in general. It may however indicate together with the highly negative correlation between SAT scores and ELL students that an earlier improvement of English as the teaching and learning language is necessary. Since the SAT scores are the average score for each school a lower value does not mean that sending one’s own child to this school will cause a bad SAT score later on.
